<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFQuraishi2006">Quraishi, Asifa (2006), "Interpreting the Qur'an and the Constitution: Similarities in the Use of Text, Tradition, and Reason in Islamic and American Jurisprudence", <i>Cardozo Law Review</i> <b>28</b>: 67–121 [68]</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Interpreting+the+Qur%27an+and+the+Constitution%3A+Similarities+in+the+Use+of+Text%2C+Tradition%2C+and+Reason+in+Islamic+and+American+Jurisprudence&amp;rft.jtitle=Cardozo+Law+Review&amp;rft.aulast=Quraishi&amp;rft.aufirst=Asifa&amp;rft.au=Quraishi%2C+Asifa&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.volume=28&amp;rft.pages=67%E2%80%93121+%5B68%5D&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Sharia"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>:
<blockquote class="templatequote">
<div>
<p>"This article will identify several types of interpretive methods which appear prominently in both Islamic and American jurisprudence, and will then follow the legal debates between them within each system, noting the significant parallels along the way. Specifically, we will study: (1) plain meaning literalism, (2) historical understanding “originalism,” and (3) reference to underlying purpose and spirit."</p>
</div>
</blockquote>
</li>
